%N A084974 Primes that show the slow decrease in the larger values of the Andrica function Af(k) = sqrt(p(k+1)) - sqrt(p(k)), where p(k) denotes the k-th prime.
%C A084974 a(n) are the primes p(k) such that Af(k) > Af(m) for all m > k. This sequence relies on a heuristic calculation and there is no proof that it is correct.
%D A084974 R. K. Guy, "Unsolved Problems in Number Theory", Springer-Verlag 1994, A8, p. 21.
%D A084974 P. Ribenboim, "The Little Book of Big Primes", Springer-Verlag 1991, p. 143.
%H A084974 Harry J. Smith, <a href="/A084974/b084974.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..128</a>
%H A084974 J. M. Flagg, Louis H. Kauffman, and Divyamaan Sahoo, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.05603">Primes Between Squares - Commentary on Appendix 8 of Laws Of Form</a>, arXiv:2511.05603 [math.NT], 2025. See pp. 24, 52.
%H A084974 Harry J. Smith, <a href="https://www.oocities.org/hjsmithh/PrimeSR/index.html">Andrica's Conjecture</a>.
%H A084974 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/AndricasConjecture.html">Andrica's Conjecture</a>.
%e A084974 a(3)=1327 because p(217)=1327, p(218)=1361 and Af(217) = sqrt(1361) - sqrt(1327) = 0.463722... is larger than any value of Af(m) for m>217.
